               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18341016-33-person412">
                  HENRY 
                  JOHN GREENING
               <interp inst="t18341016-33-person412" type="surname" value="JOHN GREENING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18341016-33-person412" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18341016-33-person412" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was my <rs id="t18341016-33-deflabel180" type="occupation">errand-boy</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18341016-33-defend409 t18341016-33-deflabel180"></join> - I missed the articles stated, and on the day following I charged him with them - he denied all knowledge of them- I told him I would forgive him, if he would confess, but he would not - the sugar-tongs and the nut-crackers were afterwards found at Mr. Lowther's, the pawnbroker.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18341016-33-person413">
                  JOHN 
                  BULLWORTHY
               <interp inst="t18341016-33-person413" type="surname" value="BULLWORTHY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18341016-33-person413" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18341016-33-person413" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner on the evening of 29th September - he came to our shop, and wished to know if these were silver - I asked whose they were - he said, his own, and he had just picked them up in the road - he left the shop, and came again in about an hour, and another boy with him, who said he saw the prisoner pick them up- I said I should detain them both, which I did.</p>
